 * Salsa grammar.  Using JavaCC Java1.1 grammar example as a starting point.
 *
 * Author: Carlos Varela cvarela@uiuc.edu 1999/09/03.
 *
 * Main changes in version 0.1 include:
 *
 * - Support for actor message sending via:
 *     actor:message(arguments);
 * - Support for token-passing continuations:
 *     a1:m1(args1)->a2:m2(args2,token);
 * - Support for join continuations:
 *     join(a1:m1(args1),a2:m2(args2),...)->b:n(token);
 * - "module" instead of "package". "behavior" instead of "class".
 *
 * Main changes in version 0.2 include:
 * 
 * - Fixed conflicts with "LabeledStatement" "ConditionalExpression" 
 *   and "SwitchLabel" which used ":" and got confused with message sends.
 *   Replaced ":" to "<-" for message sends and "->" to "@" for continuations.
 *   Examples above become:
 *
 *     actor<-message(arguments);
 *     a1<-m1(args1)@a2<-m2(args2,token);
 *     join(a1<-m1(args1),a2<-m2(args2),...)@b<-n(token);
 *
 * - Separated non-terminal "MessageSendSuffix" from "PrimaryExpression",
 *   which rules out incorrect expressions and make it easier to generate
 *   code for message sends.
 * - Created non-terminals for literals to ease code generation.
 * - Created "ContinuationExpression" allowing "JoinStatement"s.
 * - Incorporated in grammar rules: "token" and "currentContinuation".
 *
 */

